---
import SiteLayout from "../../../layouts/SiteLayout.astro";

const schema = [
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "Article",
    "headline": "Figma for Developers: Dev Mode, CSS Extraction, and Design Tokens",
    "description": "A comprehensive guide for developers on how to extract CSS, manage design tokens, and utilize Figma's Dev Mode effectively.",
    "author": {
      "@type": "Organization",
      "name": "siliconbased.dev"
    }
  },
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "FAQPage",
    "mainEntity": [
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What is Figma Dev Mode?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Dev Mode is a specialized workspace in Figma designed specifically for developers. It makes inspecting elements, copying code snippets (CSS, iOS, Android), and measuring spacing much easier than the standard design view."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Can Figma generate production-ready code?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Figma is excellent at generating CSS for individual elements (colors, shadows, gradients, simple layouts). However, it cannot generate production-ready React/Vue components or handle complex responsive logic without third-party plugins."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What are Design Tokens in Figma?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Design tokens are named variables (like 'color-primary-500' or 'spacing-md') that store design decisions. Developers can sync these tokens directly to their codebase (often via JSON and Style Dictionary) to keep code and design in sync."
        }
      }
    ]
  }
];
---

<SiteLayout
  site="siliconbased"
  title="Figma for Developers: Dev Mode & Design Tokens"
  description="A comprehensive guide for developers on how to extract CSS, manage design tokens, and utilize Figma's Dev Mode effectively."
  canonical="https://siliconbased.dev/figma-for-developers"
  schema={schema}
>
  <div class="page-content">
    <div class="hero">
      <h1>Figma for Developers</h1>
      <p>Bridging the gap between design and code in 2026</p>
    </div>

    <div class="back-link-container">
      <a href="/top-developer-tools-2026" class="back-link">← Back to Top 20 Developer Tools</a>
    </div>

    <section class="article-body">
      <h2>You Don't Need to Be a Designer</h2>
      <p>Figma has become the absolute standard for UI/UX design. As a frontend developer, you don't need to know how to create complex vector art, but you <em>do</em> need to know how to efficiently extract the information required to build the product.</p>

      <h3>1. Mastering Dev Mode</h3>
      <p>Figma's Dev Mode transforms the interface from a creation tool into an inspection tool.</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Measurement:</strong> Hovering over elements instantly shows the pixel distance to surrounding elements. No more guessing margins.</li>
        <li><strong>Code Generation:</strong> The right sidebar generates code snippets for CSS, Swift (iOS), and Compose (Android).</li>
        <li><strong>Asset Export:</strong> Easily mark icons and images for export as SVG, PNG, or WebP.</li>
      </ul>

      <div class="card related-card">
        <h3>AI and UI Generation</h3>
        <p>While Figma helps you inspect designs, AI assistants can help you write the structural code faster. <a href="/github-copilot-guide">Check out our guide to AI Coding Assistants</a>.</p>
      </div>

      <h3>2. Extracting CSS (The Right Way)</h3>
      <p>Figma's CSS generation is helpful, but blindly copying and pasting is dangerous. Here is what you should and shouldn't copy:</p>

      <h4>What to Copy:</h4>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Complex Gradients:</strong> Let Figma calculate the exact percentages and angles.</li>
        <li><strong>Box Shadows:</strong> Figma handles multi-layered, highly specific shadows perfectly.</li>
        <li><strong>Border Radii:</strong> Especially complex asymmetrical curves.</li>
        <li><strong>Typography Specifications:</strong> Font weights, line heights, and letter spacing.</li>
      </ul>

      <h4>What NOT to Copy:</h4>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Absolute Positioning:</strong> Unless you are actually building something absolute, ignore Figma's <code>top</code> and <code>left</code> values. Rely on Flexbox and Grid.</li>
        <li><strong>Fixed Widths/Heights:</strong> Figma designs are static. Web pages are fluid. Use <code>max-width</code>, <code>min-height</code>, or relative units instead of fixed pixel dimensions whenever possible.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>3. Design Tokens & Variables</h3>
      <p>The modern way to hand off designs is through <strong>Variables</strong> (Figma's native implementation of Design Tokens).</p>
      <p>Instead of hardcoding <code>#0052FF</code>, the designer defines a variable called <code>color-brand-primary</code>. As a developer, your job is to map these variables to your codebase, usually via CSS Custom Properties (Variables) or a Tailwind config.</p>
      <pre><code>/* How it looks in your CSS */
:root &#123;
  --color-brand-primary: #0052FF;
  --spacing-md: 16px;
  --radius-lg: 12px;
&#125;

.button &#123;
  background-color: var(--color-brand-primary);
  border-radius: var(--radius-lg);
  padding: var(--spacing-md);
&#125;</code></pre>

      <div class="card related-card">
        <h3>Building Your Setup</h3>
        <p>If you're building out frontend interfaces, make sure your editor is optimized. <a href="/vscode-deep-dive">Read our VS Code Deep Dive</a>.</p>
      </div>

      <h3>4. Essential Figma Plugins for Devs</h3>
      <p>If you need to do more than just inspect, these plugins are lifesavers:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>SVGO Compressor:</strong> Optimizes SVGs before you export them, reducing file size and cleaning up messy markup.</li>
        <li><strong>Figma to Code:</strong> Generates Tailwind CSS directly from Auto Layout frames.</li>
        <li><strong>Tokens Studio:</strong> The industry standard for syncing complex design token systems directly to GitHub via JSON.</li>
      </ul>

    </section>
  </div>

  <script is:inline>
    // Interactivity
  </script>

  <style is:inline>
    .page-content { max-width: 900px; margin: 0 auto; padding: 2rem 1.5rem; }
    .hero { text-align: center; padding: 3rem 0 2rem; }
    .hero h1 { font-size: 2.2rem; font-weight: 800; margin-bottom: 0.5rem; }
    .hero p { color: var(--text-secondary); font-size: 1.1rem; }

    .back-link-container { margin-bottom: 2rem; }
    .back-link { color: var(--accent-color); text-decoration: none; font-weight: 600; }
    .back-link:hover { text-decoration: underline; }

    .article-body { font-size: 1.1rem; line-height: 1.6; color: var(--text-primary); }
    .article-body h2 { margin-top: 2.5rem; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border-color); padding-bottom: 0.5rem; color: var(--accent-color); }
    .article-body h3 { margin-top: 2rem; }
    .article-body p { margin-bottom: 1.5rem; }
    .article-body ul { margin-bottom: 1.5rem; padding-left: 1.5rem; }
    .article-body li { margin-bottom: 0.5rem; }

    .card { background: var(--card-bg); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); border-radius: 12px; padding: 1.5rem; margin: 1.5rem 0; }

    .related-card { background: color-mix(in srgb, var(--accent-color) 5%, var(--card-bg)); border-left: 4px solid var(--accent-color); }
    .related-card h3 { margin-top: 0; font-size: 1.2rem; }
    .related-card p { margin-bottom: 0; }
    .related-card a { color: var(--accent-color); text-decoration: none; font-weight: 600; }
    .related-card a:hover { text-decoration: underline; }

    pre { background: #111; padding: 1rem; border-radius: 8px; overflow-x: auto; border: 1px solid var(--border-color); }
    code { font-family: 'Fira Code', 'JetBrains Mono', monospace; font-size: 0.9rem; color: #e2e8f0; }
    p code, li code { background: #222; padding: 0.2rem 0.4rem; border-radius: 4px; color: var(--accent-color); }
  </style>
</SiteLayout>
